ne, recorded in Latin sources both as <i>Gessoriacum</i> and as <i>Bononia</i>. The latter name is clearly the source of the modern placename. It is ostensibly a derivative of Latin <i>bonus</i> ‘good’ (compare   Bolognese  ), but may in fact come from a Gaulish element <i>bona</i> ‘foundation’. Boulogne has long been a major trading port between England and France."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Boleyne was born in 1304, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. She married John Boleyn in 1349, in Salle, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1353, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 49."},"et":{"1304–1353":"1304–1353","1300–1402":"1300–1402","1325–1351":"1325–1351","1350–1411":"1350–1411","1349":"1349","1304":"1304","1325":"1325","1402":"1402","1411":"1411","30 April 1350":"30. aprill 1350","1300":"1300","1353":"1353","1351":"1351","1350":"1350","Salle, Norfolk, England":"Salle, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","1671862, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Blickling, Norfolk, England":"Blickling, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"1304–1353":"1304–1353","1300–1402":"1300–1402","1325–1351":"1325–1351","1350–1411":"1350–1411","1349":"1349","1304":"1304","1325":"1325","1402":"1402","1411":"1411","30 April 1350":"30. huhtikuuta 1350","1300":"1300","1353":"1353","1351":"1351","1350":"1350","Salle, Norfolk, England":"Salle, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","1671862, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Blickling, Norfolk, England":"Blickling, Norfolk, England"},"fr":{"1304–13